  <h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Decode DOCG vs DOC Labels for Quality Hierarchy</strong> - Prosecco di Conegliano e Valdobbiadene DOCG represents the apex tier, with stricter yield limits (13.5 tons/hectare vs 18 for DOC) and mandatory hand-harvesting on steep slopes. Asolo Prosecco DOCG offers a middle ground with mineral-driven complexity. Basic Prosecco DOC delivers consistent quality at lower price points but lacks the terroir expression of hillside vineyards.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Match Sweetness Levels to Your Wine Moment</strong> - Brut Nature (0-3g/L residual sugar) pairs brilliantly with raw seafood and showcases pure Glera character, while Extra Dry (12-17g/L) paradoxically tastes drier than Dry (17-32g/L) due to higher acidity balancing the sugar. Dry grade works best with spicy Asian cuisine where the slight sweetness tames heat.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve at Precise 42-46°F for Optimal Expression</strong> - Unlike Champagne which can handle slightly warmer service, Prosecco's delicate perlage and fruit-forward profile demands colder temperatures. Inferior bottles become flabby above 50°F, while premium DOCG expressions maintain structure even at the higher end of this range, revealing more complex pear and white flower notes.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Choose Flute vs Tulip Glass Based on Quality Level</strong> - Basic Prosecco DOC performs well in traditional flutes that concentrate the mousse, but DOCG-level bottles deserve tulip-shaped glasses that allow aromatics to develop. The wider bowl reveals the mineral complexity and honeyed notes that justify the premium price point.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Understand Perlage Differences Across Styles</strong> - Charmat method Prosecco produces larger, more aggressive bubbles than Champagne's mousse, but look for persistent bead formation—cheap bottles lose effervescence within minutes. Premium producers like Bisol and Nino Franco achieve finer bubbles through longer secondary fermentation (minimum 30 days vs standard 20).</li>
  
  <li><strong>Skip Decanting Entirely—It's Counterproductive</strong> - Prosecco's charm lies in its immediate accessibility and vibrant CO2. Any decanting or excessive agitation strips the wine of its essential character. Even vintage-dated Prosecco should be opened and served immediately, as the style doesn't benefit from aeration like still wines.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Drink Within 12-18 Months for Peak Expression</strong> - Unlike Champagne's aging potential, Prosecco reaches its peak shortly after disgorgement and begins declining after two years. Check the back label for bottling dates—even premium DOCG bottles lose their signature green apple crispness and develop oxidative notes beyond 24 months.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Identify Superior Producers by Vineyard Practices</strong> - Look for "Rive" designations on DOCG labels, indicating single-commune production from steeper slopes with better drainage. Producers like Cartizze (the grand cru of Prosecco) command premium prices but deliver honeyed complexity impossible to achieve from valley floor vineyards used in basic DOC production.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically across quality tiers, making storage decisions crucial for maximizing your investment. Understanding how different styles evolve helps determine optimal drinking windows and proper cellaring techniques.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Quality Level</h3>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> reaches peak quality within 12-18 months of release, with fresh fruit aromatics beginning to fade after two years. The tank method's emphasis on primary fruit flavors means extended aging offers little benefit.</p>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOCG Superiore</strong> from Conegliano-Valdobbiadene can develop beautifully for 3-5 years, particularly single-vineyard expressions. The hillside terroir's mineral complexity emerges as initial citrus brightness mellows into honeyed stone fruit nuances.</p>

<p><strong>Franciacorta DOCG</strong> demonstrates exceptional longevity, with vintage releases improving for 8-12 years. Extended lees aging during production creates complex autolytic flavors—brioche, hazelnut, and mushroom—that continue evolving in bottle.</p>

<h3>Evolution and Storage Requirements</h3>

<p>Properly aged prosecco develops greater textural integration as aggressive bubbles soften into creamy mousse. Primary fruit transforms from bright apple-pear to richer quince and dried fruit characters, while mineral undertones become more pronounced.</p>

<p>Store bottles horizontally at 50-55°F with 70% humidity to maintain cork integrity. Unlike still wines, prosecco's pressure makes temperature stability critical—fluctuations can cause cork failure and wine loss.</p>

<h3>Recognizing Proper Development</h3>

<p>Well-aged prosecco shows deeper golden color and more complex aromatics, with bubbles becoming finer and more persistent. Warning signs include browning beyond light gold, flat or overly aggressive bubbles, and oxidized aromas resembling sherry or vinegar.</p>

<p>Peak drinking windows align with style: consume DOC within two years, DOCG within five years, and reserve Franciacorta selections for special occasions after 5-8 years of proper cellaring.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Prosecco DOCG and DOC quality levels?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco DOCG represents the highest quality tier, produced exclusively in the historic Conegliano Valdobbiadene and Asolo regions with stricter regulations and lower yields. DOC Prosecco covers a much larger area across nine provinces and allows higher production volumes, resulting in more accessible pricing but generally lighter, less complex wines. DOCG bottles typically offer more concentrated flavors, better aging potential, and greater terroir expression from hillside vineyards.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do Brut, Extra Dry, and Dry Prosecco sweetness levels compare?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Despite confusing names, "Dry" Prosecco is actually the sweetest style with 17-32 grams of residual sugar per liter, while "Extra Dry" falls in the middle at 12-17 grams, and "Brut" is the driest at under 12 grams. Extra Dry represents the traditional Prosecco style and pairs excellently with appetizers, while Brut works better with seafood and offers a more food-friendly profile. Dry Prosecco complements spicy Asian cuisine and desserts beautifully.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeled text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Prosecco producers offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Mid-tier producers like Bisol, La Marca, and Mionetto consistently deliver excellent quality-to-price ratios, offering authentic Prosecco character without premium markups. For budget-friendly options, look for DOC Prosecco from established cooperatives like Cantina Produttori di Valdobbiadene, which maintains quality standards while keeping prices accessible. Avoid the cheapest supermarket brands, as they often lack the fresh, vibrant fruit character that defines good Prosecco.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I choose vintage or non-vintage Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Non-vintage Prosecco represents 95% of production and should be consumed within 1-2 years for optimal freshness and bright acidity. Vintage Prosecco, labeled "Millesimato," comes from exceptional harvest years and offers more complexity, concentration, and aging potential of 3-5 years. Choose vintage for special occasions when you want more sophisticated flavor development, but stick with non-vintage for everyday drinking and casual celebrations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Prosecco di Conegliano Valdobbiadene and other regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Conegliano Valdobbiadene DOCG represents Prosecco's historic heartland, where steep hillside vineyards and unique microclimates create wines with greater minerality, complexity, and aging potential. These wines typically show more pronounced stone fruit flavors, floral aromatics, and a distinctive saline finish compared to the broader DOC zones. The subzone of Cartizze within this region produces the most prestigious and expensive Prosecco, known for its exceptional elegance and finesse.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long does Prosecco stay fresh after opening?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Prosecco maintains its best quality for 1-3 days after opening when properly stored in the refrigerator with a sparkling wine stopper. The wine loses carbonation quickly due to its lighter pressure compared to Champagne, so consume it as soon as possible for optimal effervescence. Higher-quality DOCG Prosecco may retain some appeal for up to 5 days, while lower-tier DOC versions often taste flat by day two.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are expensive Proseccos worth the premium over budget options?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Premium Proseccos from DOCG regions justify their higher cost through superior fruit concentration, more complex flavor profiles, and better integration of bubbles and acidity. While a $12 DOC Prosecco serves well for casual drinking, a $25-35 DOCG bottle offers significantly more sophistication with layers of pear, apple, and mineral notes plus better food-pairing versatility. The sweet spot for quality-conscious buyers lies in the $18-25 range from established DOCG producers.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What common mistakes should I avoid when selecting Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Avoid buying Prosecco that's been sitting on warm store shelves or in direct sunlight, as heat destroys the fresh fruit character essential to good Prosecco. Don't assume all Italian sparkling wine labeled "Prosecco" is authentic – look for official DOCG or DOC designations and the Glera grape variety. Most importantly, never age Prosecco like Champagne; these wines are meant for immediate consumption and deteriorate rapidly after their second year.</p>
  </div>
</div>

